"1335":"1335","1300":"1300","1344":"1344","1322":"1322","1331":"1331","1265":"1265","Authuille, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Authuille, Somme, Hauts-de-France, Frankrijk","Authuille, Somme, Picardie, França":"Authuille, Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk","Ham, Péronne, Somme, Picardie, France":"Péronne, Somme, Hauts-de-France, Frankrijk","Ham, Somme, Picardie, França":"Ham, Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk","Ham 80400":"Ham, Nyong-et-Kéllé, Centre, Kameroen"},"en":{"1275–1331":"1275–1331","1265–1322":"1265–1322","1274–Male":"1274–Deceased","1305–1344":"1305–1344","1248–1335":"1248–1335","1295–1357":"1295–1357","1300–Female":"1300–Deceased","1230–1326":"1230–1326","1240–1326":"1240–1326","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1230":"1230","1295":"1295","1240":"1240","1305":"1305","1326":"1326","1248":"1248","1357":"1357","1335":"1335","1300":"1300","1344":"1344","1322":"1322","1331":"1331","1265":"1265","Authuille, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Authuille, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France","Authuille, Somme, Picardie, França":"Authuille, Somme, Picardie, France","Ham, Péronne, Somme, Picardie, France":"Péronne, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France","Ham, Somme, Picardie, França":"Ham, Somme, Picardie, France","Ham 80400":"Ham, Nyong-et-Kéllé, Centre, Cameroon","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Ham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Korean Young, Ok, Nam, Chul, Eun Hee, Eun Young, Hae Jung, Il Hwa.","English (mainly southwestern) and German: variant of   Hamm  .","Dutch: topographic name from <i>ham</i> ‘land in a river bend’, ‘enclosed meadow’, or a habitational name from any of several country houses and places called De(n) Ham. Compare   Van Ham   and   Vanderham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hamme","meanings":["Flemish (<b>Van Hamme</b>): variant of   Ham   2, particularly referring to Hamme, a place in East Flanders.","German and English: variant of   Hamm  ."]},{"name":"Hamm","meanings":["English (London): topographic name for someone who lived at a place called from Middle English <i>ham(me)</i>, <i>hom(me)</i> (Old English <i>hamm</i>), which meant ‘land in a river bend’, ‘land hemmed in by marshland’, ‘wet land hemmed in by higher ground’, ‘river meadow’, or ‘cultivated plot on the edge of woodland or moor’. The topographic term is found mainly in the South Midlands and southern England. There are many farmsteads with this name in Devon and Sussex, five more substantial settlements called Ham or Hamp in Somerset, as well as East and West Ham in Essex, and places called Ham in Gloucestershire, Hampshire, Kent, Surrey, and Wiltshire. This form of the surname is also comparatively frequent in Ireland.","German: topographic name for someone who lived on land in a river bend, Old High German <i>ham</i> (see 1 above).","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from any of numerous places called Hamm, mainly the city in Westphalia."]},{"name":"Hahm","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Korean Sung, Yong, Byung, Chang, Dong, Hyun, Jae, Jee, Jong, Jong Hun, Jong Hyun, Moon Hee, Jung Suk, Sang, Seok, Seung, Soon, Sungtae, Taeyong.","German: metonymic occupational name for a sealer of weights and measures, from Middle High German <i>hāme</i> ‘(standard) measure’.","Korean: variant of   Ham  ."]},{"name":"Hams","meanings":["English: variant of   Ham   with plural <i>-s</i> or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Blanche","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a nickname for a blonde, from <i>blanche</i>, feminine of Old French <i>blanc</i> ‘white’ (of Germanic origin). It came to be associated with the notion of whiteness as indicating purity, and was introduced into England as a given name by the Normans. A pale complexion combined with light hair was long an ideal of beauty in Europe (compare Modern English <i>fair</i>, which at first meant ‘beautiful’ and then, from the 16th century, ‘light in colouring’)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"dite","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  See  Dyte  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dyte","meanings":["English: nickname, perhaps from an unrecorded Middle English * <i>dight</i>, a side-form of Middle English  <i>dought</i> ‘brave, valiant’, and possibly derived therefore from a shortened form of Old English  <i>dyhtig</i>,  <i>dohtig</i> ‘doughty’.  Compare  Doughty  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Blanche dite Carolingienne de Ham was born in 1275, in Ham, Nyong-et-Kéllé, Centre, Cameroon, her father, Eudes de Ham, was 46 and her mother, Isabelle de Heilly, was 36. She married Gilles, Dit D'Authuille de MAILLY. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1331, in Authuille, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1275–1331":"1275–1331","1265–1322":"1265–1322","1274–Male":"1274–Surnud","1305–1344":"1305–1344","1248–1335":"1248–1335","1295–1357":"1295–1357","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1230–1326":"1230–1326","1240–1326":"1240–1326","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1230":"1230","1295":"1295","1240":"1240","1305":"1305","1326":"1326","1248":"1248","1357":"1357",